text: Commodity Movements Originating in West Virginia
label: HH1

text: In West Virginia, the CFS measured $35 billion of goods shipments weighing 234
label: TITLE

text: million tons.  West Virginia accounted for approximately 1 percent of the value and 2
label: BODY

text: percent of the weight of total U.S. shipments.  See attached table.  The CFS data cover
label: BODY

text: shipments by establishments in mining, manufacturing, wholesale, and selected retail and
label: BODY

text: service industries.  The data exclude most shipments of crude oil; therefore, the totals and
label: BODY

text: percentages do not fully reflect the contribution of pipeline shipments.
label: BODY

text: The major commodities shipped by establishments vary when measured by value
label: BODY

text: and weight.  The main commodities originating in West Virginia by value were:
label: BODY

text: chemicals or allied products; coal; primary metal products; petroleum, or coal products;
label: BODY

text: and food or kindred products.  The main commodities by weight were:  coal; petroleum
label: BODY

text: or coal products; chemicals or allied products; nonmetallic minerals; and lumber or wood
label: BODY

text: Local transportation of freight is important to West Virginiaâ€™s commerce.  The
label: BODY

text: CFS shows that in 1993, about one-quarter of the value and over one-third of the weight
label: BODY

text: of total shipments from West Virginia were shipped to destinations within the state.
label: BODY

text: About 25 percent of the value and about 41 percent of the weight of all shipments were
label: BODY

text: between places less than 50 miles apart.  In comparison, about 30 percent of the value and
label: BODY

text: 56 percent of the weight of total U.S. shipments were between places less than 50 miles
label: BODY

text: apart.  In West Virginia, about 39 percent of the value of shipments and 49 percent of the
label: BODY

text: weight of shipments were between places less than 100 miles apart.
label: BODY

text: Approximately three-quarters of the value and two-thirds of the weight of all
label: BODY

text: shipments from West Virginia went to other states.  The most important destination state
label: BODY

text: by value of shipments was Ohio.  Other important states by value were:  Virginia,
label: BODY

text: Pennsylvania, New York, and Kentucky.  Some of the most important destinations by
label: BODY

text: weight of shipments were:  Ohio, Virginia, Pennsylvania, Michigan, and North Carolina.
label: BODY

text: A large proportion of commodities were moved by trucks, about 65 percent of the
label: BODY

text: value and 29 percent of the weight.  Rail was also important, accounting for 14 percent of
label: BODY

text: the value and 43 percent of the weight of shipments.  Water transportation moved 5
label: BODY

text: percent of the value of shipments and 20 percent of the weight.
label: BODY

text: The Commodity Flow Survey (CFS) is a comprehensive effort to learn where and
label: BODY

text: how goods are shipped in the U.S. The CFS measures shipments of commodities by
label: BODY

text: establishments with paid employees and engaged in manufacturing, mining, wholesale
label: BODY

text: trade, or selected retail and services industries. Prior commodity surveys covered
label: BODY

text: shipments only by manufacturing firms. Commodity flows are estimated for a universe of
label: BODY

text: Data collected on individual shipments include total value, total weight,
label: BODY

text: commodity type, modes of transport, domestic origin and destination; data for export
label: BODY

text: shipments include the city and country of destination, mode and port of exit. Information
label: BODY

text: is also be obtained on whether shipments are containerized or a hazardous material. Some
label: BODY

text: firms provided data concerning on-site shipping facilities and access to shipping facilities,
label: BODY

text: plus data on ownership and leasing of transportation equipment.
label: BODY

text: The CFS is conducted by the Bureau of the Census as part of the Economic
label: BODY

text: Census. Funding and technical guidance is provided by the U.S. Department of
label: BODY

text: Transportation. Initiated for 1993, the CFS is scheduled for 1997 and every 5 years
label: BODY

text: thereafter for years ending in 2 and 7. Commodity surveys were conducted between 1963
label: BODY

text: and 1982, but data for 1982 were not published. No data were collected for 1987.
label: BODY

text: Participants will report for a sample of shipments during a 2-week period each quarter
label: BODY

text: The CFS is a mail-out/mail-back survey of 200,000 sampled employer
label: BODY

text: establishments in selected industries. Establishments were selected by stratified sample,
label: BODY

text: with strata based on geographic location and industry. Geographic strata are the 89
label: BODY

text: National Transportation Analysis Regions(NTARs), which provide nationwide coverage
label: BODY

text: and are aggregations of Bureau of Economic Analysis economic areas. Within the strata,
label: BODY

text: all establishments with annualized employment above a specified cutoff were selected
label: BODY

text: with certainty, and the remaining smaller establishments were sampled with probability
label: BODY

text: For 1993, each sampled establishment reported on a sample of individual
label: BODY

text: shipments during a 2 week period in each calendar quarter. In addition, about 20,000
label: BODY

text: establishments will provide information on transportation facilities and arrangements in
label: BODY

text: For further information about survey design and printed products, contact the
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: DC 20233, or by calling 301/457-2805 or 2114. For information on related data programs
